<br/>

There is another useful formula for $$\hat b_1$$:

$$
\displaystyle
\hat b_1 = r_{xy} \frac {S_y}{S_x},
$$

where:

* $$r_{xy}$$ is the [[Sample Correlation Coefficient|Sample Pearson Correlation Coefficient]] of $$x$$ and $$y$$;
* $$S_y$$ and $$S_x$$ are [[Sample Variances|Sample Variance]] of $$x$$ and $$y$$.

<br/>

This formula for the [[Slope]] of the [[Regression|Linear Regression]] line is particularly insightful for:

* $$S_y/S_x$$ is much like $$\Delta y/\Delta x$$ in the equations of "normal lines" - but unlike the latter, it does not control the "direction" (i.e. up or down)
* $$r_{xy}$$ controls the "direction"
* As $$x$$ and $$y$$ get less and less [[correlated|Pearson Correlation Coefficient]], the $$r_{xy}$$ term makes the resulting slope closer and closer to a horisontal line, which would correspond to the [[Constant Predictor]], indicating that $$x$$ does not affect $$y$$ at all

